__value__.schema:name: Derek Mahon
__value__.schema:description: Derek Mahon (born 23 November 1941) is a Northern Irish poet. He was born in Belfast Northern Ireland.

__value__.schema:name: Ronald Stein
__value__.schema:description: Ronald Stein (April 12 1930 – August 15 1988) was an American film composer.

__value__.schema:name: Ron Tarrant
__value__.schema:description: Ron Tarrant (born 11 October 1988 Calgary Alberta) is a Canadian radio Imaging Producer/Sound Designer as well as Singer/Guitarist/Producer in the Canadian band Lost In Film. Tarrant received his diploma from Southern Alberta Institute of Technology in the RTBN program (Radio Television & Broadcast News) majoring in radio.

__value__.schema:name: William Hamilton Page
__value__.schema:description: William Hamilton Page (1829–1909) was a type designer and owner of William Page & Company a leading manufacturer of wood type for letterpress printing.

__value__.schema:name: Joseph LeBoit
__value__.schema:description: Joseph Milton LeBoit (Nov. 22 1907-July 5 2002) was an American graphic artist and later psychoanalyst active in leftist politics.

__value__.schema:name: Bernard Seigal
__value__.schema:description: Bernard R. Buddy Blue Seigal (December 30 1957 – April 2 2006) was a San Diego musician music critic and writer who performed and often wrote under his stage name Buddy Blue. He was a founding member of The Beat Farmers a Southern California rock band that blended country roots music and rock 'n' roll.

__value__.schema:name: George T. Morgan
__value__.schema:description: George T. Morgan (November 24 1845 – January 4 1925) was an English United States Mint engraver who is famous for designing many popular coins such as the Morgan Dollar and the Columbian Exposition half dollar.

__value__.schema:name: Charles Codman
__value__.schema:description: Charles Codman (1800 − September 11 1842) was a noted American painter. Codman who lived his entire life in Portland Maine was known for his landscape and marine paintings.

__value__.schema:name: Anna Vaughn Hyatt Huntington
__value__.schema:additionalName: Anna Vaughn Huntington,  Anna V. Hyatt Huntington, Mrs. Archer M. Huntington,  Anna Vaughn Hyatt,  Anna V. Hyatt, Anna Hyatt Huntington

__value__.schema:name: Anna Hyatt Huntington
__value__.schema:description: Anna Vaughn Hyatt Huntington (March 10 1876 – October 4 1973) was an American sculptor and was once among New York City's most prominent sculptors. At a time when very few women were successful artists she had a thriving career. She exhibited often traveled widely received critical acclaim at home and abroad and won awards and commissions.

__value__.schema:name: John Noble (painter)
__value__.schema:description: John ('Wichita Bill') Noble was born in 1874 to an upper-middle-class family that had emigrated from England. He was a noted post-impressionist painter of cowboys sunrises and seascapes. He wore a five-gallon hat called himself the first white child born in Wichita.He often advised prospective customers not to buy his paintings.

__value__.schema:name: Norman Rockwell
__value__.schema:description: Norman Perceval Rockwell (February 3 1894 – November 8 1978) was a 20th-century American painter and illustrator. His works enjoy a broad popular appeal in the United States for their reflection of American culture. Rockwell is most famous for the cover illustrations of everyday life scenarios he created for The Saturday Evening Post magazine for more than four decades.
